text: Arch. Pharm. Res.  https://doi.org/10.1007/s12272-020-01288-1 Bioactive natural products from the genus Salinospora: a review Haerin Kim1 · Sohee Kim1 · Minju Kim1 ·  Chaeyoung Lee1 · Inho Yang2 · Sang‑Jip Nam3  Received: 25 August 2020 / Accepted: 13 November 2020  © The Pharmaceutical Society of Korea 2020 Abstract  Actinomycetes  are  an  important  source  for  bioactive secondary metabolites. Among them, the genus  Salinispora is one of the first salt obligatory marine spe- cies worldwide and is typically found in various types of  substrates in tropical and subtropical marine environments  including  sediments  and  marine  organisms.  This  genus  produces a wide range of chemical scaffolds and bioactive  compounds such as lomaiviticins, cyclomarins, rifamycins,  salinaphthoquinones, and salinosporamides. This review  arranged Salinispora derived secondary metabolites accord- ing to the three species that comprise the genus. Moreover,  muta- and semi-synthesis analogs derived from salinospora- mide were also described in this review. Keywords  Salinispora · Marine natural products ·  Actinomycetes · Salinispora arenicola · Salinispora  tropica · Salinispora pacifica Haerin Kim, Sohee Kim, and Minju Kim have contributed  equally to this work. 1  The Graduate School of Industrial Pharmaceutical Sciences,  2  Department of Convergence Study on the Ocean Science  and Technology, Korea Maritime and Ocean University,  Pusan 49112, Korea 3  Department of Chemistry and Nanoscience, Ewha Womans  Ewha Womans University, Seoul 03760, Korea University, Seoul 03760, Korea

The genus Salinispora was among the first reported obligate  marine actinomycetes, meaning that it requires salt to grow  (Mincer et al. 2002). This genus is distributed worldwide  in tropical and subtropical marine environments, sediments  from both beaches and the ocean bottom (He et al. 2001),  and marine organisms such as algae and sponges (Jensen  et al. 2005; Kim et al. 2005; Vidgen et al. 2012). This genus  comprises three species: Salinispora tropica, Salinispora  arenicola, and Salinispora pacifica, which share 16S rRNA  sequence similarities of more than 99.2% (Jensen and Maf- nas 2006). This high similarity degree exceeds the suggested  species-defining 16S rRNA similarity threshold, and there- fore DNA–DNA hybridization analysis has been necessary  to distinguish the three species. Moreover, S. tropica isolates  from Caribbean sediments have been used as a model for the  study of bacterial biogeography (Freel et al. 2012). However, studies on this genus not only focus on bioge- ography but also on biosynthetic potential. Over 50 natu- ral products have been isolated from this genus, as well as  inspired many muta- and semi-synthesis compounds. In this  review, we describe the chemical structure and bioactivities  of natural products isolated from the genus Salinispora, as  well as their synthetic analogs. The compounds were cat- egorized according to the strain from which the derived (S.  tropica, S. arenicola, and S. pacifica). All compounds are  discussed in alphabetical order, with the exception of salino- sporamides from S. tropica. Online ISSN 1976-3786 Print ISSN 0253-6269

Salinosporamide A (1) was first isolated from Salinispora  tropica strain CNB-392 (Feling et al. 2003). Salinospora- mide A (1) possesses an unusual fused γ-lactam-β-lactone  ring  structure  including  clasto-lactacystin-β-lactone  (Feling et al. 2003; Stadler et al. 2004). Clasto-lactacystin- β-lactone is also known as omuralide and was first isolated  from Streptomyces lactacystinaeus (Corey and Li 1999).  Omuralide (2) binds irreversibly to the 20S proteasome  (Adams 2004), which possesses three proteolytic subunits  (β5, β2, and β1), contain active sites with different spe- cificities, such as chymotrypsin-like (CT-L), trypsin-like  (T-L), and caspase-like (C-L) activity, respectively. The  anti-apoptotic pathway is activated when the 26S protea- some, which is in turn composed of two 19S regulatory  cap subunits and the 20S proteasome, converts the NF-κB  p105 precursor to the active p50 subunit through degrada- tion. However, inhibiting the 26S proteasome by binding  proteins to the 20S proteasome has a protective effect on  the anti-apoptotic signal pathway. Therefore, compounds  that bind to the 20S proteasome are promising agents for  cancer treatment. Interestingly, salinosporamide A (1) pos- sesses a 35 times more binding affinity for the 20S protea- some than omuralide (2). Furthermore, treatment with 1 reduced pro- liferation  in  Velcade-resistant  multiple  myeloma  cells  (Richardson et al. 2003). Therefore, 1 was proposed as a  potent anti-cancer agent and finally entered phase I human  clinical trials against multiple myeloma only 3 years after  its discovery (Chauhan et al. 2005). Marizomib, the phar- macological  name  of  salinosporamide  A  (1),  was  well  tolerated  and  exhibited  significant  activity  in  patients  with heavily pretreated relapsed and/or refractory multi- ple myeloma (RRMM) in phase I clinical trials (Harrison  et al. 2015). In 2017, phase III clinical trials for marizomib  were initiated.

Secondary metabolites isolated from Salinispora  tropica and their biological activities Salinosporamides B and C (3 and 4, Fig. 1) were dis- covered  in S.  tropica  strain  CNB-392  (Williams  et  al.  2005). Compound 3 is the deschloro analog of 1, which  comprises acetate, β-hydroxy-2′-cyclohexenylalanine, and  butyrate units. Salinosporamide C (4) is an analog of 1  Salinosporamides 3–17 were analyzed to elucidate their  bioactivities. As a result, compound 3 was found to pos- sess cytotoxicity against human multiple myeloma cell line  RPM8226, with an  IC50 concentration of 6100 nM and an  inhibitory effect on the growth of human colon cancer cells  (HCT-116) at a  GI50 concentration of 20,000 nM. In con- trast, compound 4 had an extremely weak inhibitory effect  on HCT-116 cell proliferation  (GI50 > 27,500 nM) (Wil- liams et al. 2005). Additionally, it has been reported that  compounds 5–10 inhibited the activity of 20S proteasome  (Table 1) (Reed et al. 2007). Moreover, in CT-L activity  inhibitory tests, compound 11 was 20-fold less effective than  1  (IC50 = 52 nM for 11 and  IC50 = 2.6 nM for 1, respectively)  (Macherla et al. 2005; Potts et al. 2006; Manam et al. 2008;  Potts and Lam 2010).

The anti-cancer effects of compounds 13–17 have been  tested in several cell lines including human colon cancer  (HCT-116), melanoma (LOC-IMVI), non-small lung cancer  (HOP-92), ovarian cancer (OVCAR-3), and prostate cancer  (PC-3). Low  GI50 values indicate a high inhibitory activ- ity against the tested cancer cells (Williams et al. 2005).  Additionally, the  GI50 values of 13–17 against the National  Cancer Institute (NCI) panel of 60 human tumor cell lines  (mean  GI50) were also determined. In this context, low mean   GI50 values indicate a broad activity spectrum against differ- ent cancer cells. Compound 17 displayed a  GI50 of 31 µM  on the HCT-116 cell line. Compound 15 had a weak inhibi- tory activity against HCT-116, with a  GI50 value exceeding  310 µM and a low mean  GI50 of 58 µM on the 60-cell panel.  with a hexahydro-3H-pyrrolo-[1,2a]-indol-3,6-dione struc- ture containing γ-lactam similar to 1. Salinosporamides D–J (5–11, Fig. 1) were isolated from  S. tropica strain NPS000465 and most of them were com- pounds with modifications of the side chain at C-2 position  (Reed et al. 2007). Salinosporamides D (5) and E (6) are  only subtly different, with their C-2 attached to either methyl  or propyl groups, respectively. Salinosporamide F (7) is a  C-2 epimer of 1 and salinosporamide G (8) is a C-2 epimer  of 5. Salinosporamide I (10) possesses an ethyl group at the  C-5 ring junction, and salinosporamide J (11) has a dehy- droxylated C-5. Salinosporamide H (9), a C-2 epimer of 3,  and bromosalinosporamide (12), a brominated analog of 1,  were also isolated from this strain.

Five more salinosporamides (13–17, Fig. 1) were isolated  from strain CNB-392 (Williams et al. 2005). Compound 13  is a methyl ester analog of the seco-acid of 1. Compound 14  is a tetrahydrofuran analog of 13, which does not contain  the chloroethyl group. Compound 15 possesses an α,β,γ,δ- unsaturated γ-lactam moiety in which an hydroxyl group at  C-5 has been eliminated to form a double bond. Compounds  16 and 17 are C-4 configurational isomer set which possess  an α,β,γ,δ-unsaturated γ-lactam structure connected with the  intact cyclohexene group at the C-5. Bioactive natural products from the genus Salinospora: a review   Fig. 1   Chemical structures of natural salinosporamides 1–17  Compounds 13–16 had much weaker inhibitory effects on  HCT-116 proliferation than that of compound 1  (GI50 of  35 nM for 1;  GI50 of 31,000 nM for 17). Therefore, the anti- cancer properties of compound 1 were largely attributed to  β-lactone moiety, as β-lactone was the only structural differ- ence between compounds 1 and 17. Additionally, the  GI50  of compound 3 was slightly lower than that of 17, suggest- ing that the chloroethyl group may also confer anti-cancer  properties. Salinosporamides production via muta‑synthesis A study on S. tropica strain CNB-440 metabolic engineer- ing resulted in salinosporamide X1–X7 (18–24) as in Fig. 2.  Compounds  18,  19,  20  and 24  had  modified  cyclohex- ene rings corresponding to the cyclohexyl, cyclopentyl,  cyclobutyl and cyclopentenyl groups, respectively (Nett  et al. 2009). The inhibitory effects of compounds 18–24 on  CT-L activities and HCT-116 proliferation were then evalu- ated. Compound 24 exhibited stronger inhibitory activity

than compound 1 on both assays. Compound 24 showed  a slightly lower  IC50 value for CT-L activity than that of 1  and inhibited the growth of HCT-116 cells more strongly  than compound 1  (IC50 = 2.2 nM for 24,  IC50 = 2.5 nM for 1;   GI50 = 5.9 nM for 24,  GI50 = 35 nM for 1). Moreover, com- pound 19 displayed a slightly higher  IC50 value for the inhi- bition of CT-L activity (9.3 nM) and HCT-116 proliferation  (54 nM) compared to compound 1. Salinosporamides production via semi‑synthesis Fluorosalinosporamide (25) was synthetically prepared  from 1, albeit with low yields. Compound 25 inhibited  CT-L  activity,  with  an  IC50  of  9.2  nM  (Manam  et  al.  2008). Using a semi-synthesis approach, the production  of  25  from  a salL −FlA+  mutant  of S.  tropica  rendered  higher compound yields (Eustáquio et al. 2010). Keto- salinosporamide  (26)  was  obtained  from  the  oxidation  of  the  hydroxyl  group  at  the  C-5  of  compound 1,  and  subsequent  reduction  of 26  resulted  in  the  production  a m o l e y m e l p i t l u m n a m u h e k i l - n i s p y r t o m y h c , y t i c i x o t o t y c Bioactive natural products from the genus Salinospora: a review

of C-5-epi-salinosporamide (27) (Macherla et al. 2005).  Compounds 26 and 27 exhibited a weak inhibitory effect,  according to the CT-L assay. In the same study, a series  of  modifications  at  the  cyclohexene  ring  of  compound  1  were  explored.  Epoxidation  of  the  cyclohexene  ring  of 1 resulted in NPI-2060 (28) and NPI-2061 (29). The  introduction of halohydrin to the double bond yielded the  chlorinated product NPI-2064 (30). Moreover, a reduc- tion at the site produced salinosporamide X1 (18), which  possesses a saturated cyclohexane ring. As summarized  in Table 1, these salinosporamides exhibited promising  bioactivities  in  many  bioassays.  Compound 18  had  an   IC50 of 20 nM for the inhibition of CT-L activity, which  is 10 times higher than that of compound 1. Furthermore,  although compounds 28 and 29 are structurally similar,  the  IC50 of 28 was far lower than that of 29. Therefore, the  stereochemistry of epoxide rings appeared to be crucial  for 20S proteasome inhibition. Compound 30 had a lower  CT-L-inhibiting activity than 1  (IC50 of 8,200 nM for 30). NPI-2157 (31) and NPI-2167 (32) were produced by add- ing a carbonyl group to the cyclohexene ring of compound  1. However, the bioactivities of these two compounds have  not yet been reported (Potts and Lam 2010).

The Introduction of semi-synthetic modifications at C-2  has yielded four derivatives of 1 (33–36, Fig. 3) (Macherla  et al. 2005; Potts et al. 2006). Iodosalinosporamide (33)  and  hydroxy-salinosporamide  (34)  were  synthesized  by  displacing the chloroethyl group at C-2 of compound 1 to  iodoethyl and hydroxyl groups, respectively. Azidosalino- sporamide (35) and thiocyanosalinosporamide (36) were  synthesized by replacing the hydroxyl group at C-13 in 34  to  N3 and -SCN groups, respectively. Compounds 33–36  exhibited  CT-L  activity  IC50  values  lower  than  15  nM.  Other functional groups were introduced at C-2 such as  mesyl, tosyl and dansyl (37–39, Fig. 3) which were semi- synthetically  prepared  from  compound 34.  Tosylsalino- sporamide (38) had a similar CT-L activity  IC50 to that of  compound 1, whereas mesylsalinosporamide (37) and dan- sylsalinosporamide (39) showed slightly higher  IC50 values  than 1  (IC50 = 2.5 ± 1.2 nM for  1,  IC50 = 4.3 ± 0.8 nM for  37,  IC50 = 2.5 ± 0.4 nM for  38,  IC50 = 3.0 ± 0.5 nM for  39)  (Manam et al. 2008).

Thioester  derivatives  of  salinosporamide  A  (1)  were  also semi-synthesized (40–45, Fig. 3) (Reed et al. 2007).  Compounds 41 and 42 were 20S proteasome inhibitors that  exhibited 3.6- and 1.5-fold higher  IC50 values than com- pound 1, respectively. Compound 43 is a thioester derivative  of compound 3 with a 2-fold higher CT-L activity of  IC50  values than 3. Compounds 44 and 45 were obtained through  intra-molecular chlorine elimination from 42 to 41, respec- tively. The  IC50 values of compounds 40–45 indicate that the  β-lactone ring and the chloroethyl group are important for  the bioactivity of these compounds. Fig. 2   Chemical structures of  salinosporamides produced via  muta-synthesis Antiprotealide (46, Fig.  4) was isolated from S. tropica  strain CNB-440, CNB-476, and NPS-21184 (Manam et al.  2009).  Compound 46  is  a  rare  case  of  a  natural  prod- uct that was synthetically obtained before its isolation  (Reddy et al. 2005; McGlinchey et al. 2008). The chemi- cal structure of 46 is a hybrid of 1 and 2 with an isopropyl  group displacing the cyclohexane ring of compound 1.  The CT-L activity  IC50 of 46 was 10 times higher than  that of 1  (IC50 = 31 ± 5 nM for  46). Compound 46 exhib- ited weaker activity than 1 in a cytotoxicity test using the  human multiple myeloma cell line RPMI8226 (Table 1)  (Manam et al. 2009). The weaker CT-L inhibiting activity  of 46 compared to that of 1 indicated that the chloroethyl  group at C-2 is more crucial for CT-L inhibition activity  than cyclohexene moiety at C-6.

Collectively, compound 24 displayed the highest inhib- itory effect on CT-L activity with an  IC50 value of 2.2 nM  and was the only compound that inhibited the growth of  HCT-116 at a lower concentration than 1  (GI50 = 35 nM  for 1,  GI50 = 5.9 nM for 24). Compound 38 was the com- pound with the strongest inhibitory effect, with an  IC50  of 2.5 nM in the T-L activity assay; however, its CT-L  inhibitory activity was 3-fold lower than that of com- pound 1. Additionally, compound 41 exhibited the most  potent cytotoxicity against human multiple myeloma cell  line RPM18226. Overall, β-lactone moiety and the presence of a chloro- ethyl group at C-2 are crucial to inhibit 20S proteasome  activity and HCT-116 growth. Moreover, when comparing  the reported  IC50 and  GI50 values for compounds 1–46,  the chloroethyl group at C-2 was found to contribute more  heavily to their bioactivities than β-lactone. Lomaiviticin C (47, Fig. 5) is a glycosylated diazofluorene  polyketide that was isolated from S. tropica strain CNB- 440 through bioactivity-guided genome mining (Kersten  et al. 2013a). Compound 47 was also obtained from S.  pacifica strain DPJ-0019 in addition to six analogs (Woo  et al. 2012).

Lymphostin (48, Fig. 6) was isolated from S. tropica strain  CNB-440 but was originally isolated from Streptomyces sp.  strain KY11783 (Nagata et al. 1997; Miyanaga et al. 2011).  Compound 48 possesses a novel tricyclic aromatic alkaloid  with a pyrrolo[4,3,2-de] quinoline skeleton. This fused aro- matic ring system is rare among natural products, and pla- kinidines were the only compound known to possess this  type of skeleton before 48 was discovered. Compound 48  exhibited a potent mTOR inhibition and cytotoxicity with  an  IC50 value of 7 nM (Miyanaga et al. 2011). Salinilactam A (49, Fig. 7) belongs to the polyene macro- lactam class of natural products and was isolated from S.  tropica strain CNB-440. This compound consists of two  isolated polyene fragments, a 1,2,3,5-tetrahydroxy alkane  moiety, three methyl groups, and an amide functional group  (Udwary et al. 2007). Notably, compound 49 was used as a  model to demonstrate the potential of bioinformatic analyses  to elucidate chemical structure. Sioxanthin  (50,  (2′ S)-1′-(β-D-glucopyranosyloxy)-3′,4′- didehydro-1′,2′-dihydro-φ,ψ-caroten-2′-ol,  Fig.  8)  was  isolated  from S.  tropica  strain  CNB-440  (Richter  et  al.  2015). This compound possesses an unprecedented struc- ture despite belonging to the carotenoid family. One end of  the molecule is a glycosylated group and the opposite end  Fig. 7   Chemical structure of salinilactam A (49) contains an aryl moiety. However, the end structures of com- pound 50 have only been identified separately in carotenoids.  The aromatic end of carotenoids was found in many Strep- tomyces strains (Krügel et al. 1999). The other end contains  a 1′-glycosylation, a 2′-hydroxyl, and a 3′,4′-desaturation,  which are known elements of pheixanthophyl isolated from  a single Mycobacterium phlei strain (Hertzberg and Liaaen  Jensen 1967; Takano et al. 2005).

Sporolides A (51) and B (52) were isolated from S. tropica  strain CNB-392 (Fig. 9) (Buchanan et al. 2005). Compounds  51 and 52 are unique secondary metabolites, as 23 out of the  24 carbons in their structure are oxygenated or  sp2 hybrid- ized. The lower cyclohexanone-half portion of the sporolides  resembles cyclohexenone vertinoid polyketides, which have  been isolated from a marine fungal strain Trichoderma.  However, structures containing the upper portion of the  molecule had not been reported prior to the discovery of the  sporolides. The only difference between compounds 51 and  52 is the location of a chlorine atom. Compounds 51 and 52  did not show any biological activities when screened against  human  colon  carcinoma  HCT-116,  nor  did  they  exhibit  antibacterial activity in bioassays with methicillin-resistant  Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) and vancomycin-resistant  Enterococcus faecium (VRE). Secondary metabolites isolated from Salinispora  arenicola and their biological activities Arenamides A–C (53–55, Fig. 10) are cyclohexadepsipep- tides isolated from S. arenicola strain CNT-088, which  was isolated from marine sediments around Fiji Island  (Asolkar et al. 2009). Compounds 53 and 54 contain five  amino acid subunits: a phenylalanine, an alanine, a valine,  a glycine, and a leucine. not  contain  an  aromatic  ring  and  possesses  a  methio- nine instead of a phenylalanine residue. Compounds 53  and 54 were found to inhibit nuclear factor kappa-light- chain-enhancer of activated B cells (NF-κB) induced by  tumor necrosis factor (TNF) in 293/NFκB-Luc human  embryonic kidney cells and also inhibited nitric oxide  (NO) and prostaglandin E2 (PGE2) production in RAW  264.7 cells. Fig. 11   Chemical structures of arenicolides A–C (56–58) Arenicolides A–C (56–58, Fig. 11), produced by S. areni- cola strain CNR-005 from the island of Guam, are macrolide  polyketides (Williams et al. 2007b). These compounds pos- sess 26-membered polyunsaturated lactone rings, which  Fig. 12   Chemical structure of arenimycins A (59) and B (60) contain repeated hydroxyl and methoxyl functional groups.  However, unlike the other two arenicolides, compound 58  has a tetrahydrofuran ring instead of a trisubstituted epox- ide, which is connected to an n-propyl chain. Only 56 has  cytotoxicity toward the HCT-116, with an  IC50 value of  36.26 µM. Bioactive natural products from the genus Salinospora: a review

Arenimycin A (59, Fig. 12), an antibiotic against rifampin-  and  methicillin-resistant  Staphylococcus  aureus,  was  identified in S. arenicola strain CNR-647 collected from  a  mangrove  channel  at  Sweetings  Cay,  Grand  Bahama  Island (Asolkar et al. 2010). This compound belongs to  the benzo[α]naphtacene quinone class and contains a hex- opyranose sugar with a hydroxyl group at the C-4′ position.  The ring system of quinones in arenimycins is very rare in  nature and has only been reported in ansacarbomitocins,  BE 19412A, collinone, G 2A, G 2N, and KS 61,910. Com- pound 59 exhibited antibiotic activities against various drug- resistant Staphylococcus and Enterococcus strain, as well as  cytotoxicity against the HCT-116 cell line, with an  IC50 of  1.74 µM. Its minimum inhibition concentration (MIC) value  is ≤ 1.50 µM, which indicates antibacterial activity toward  human Gram (+) pathogens such as various MRSA strains,  Enterococcus faecalis, and Enterococcus faecium. This com- pound is also known to inhibit Mycobacterium bovis bacille  Calmette-Guérin at a 1.50 µM concentration. The arenimycin A derivative, a glycosylated aromatic  polyketide arenimycin B (60, Fig. 12) was discovered from  the strain CNB-527 with a coproduction of 59 (Kersten et al.  2013b). Glycosylated compounds consist of an aglycone and  one or multiple glycosyl units, which often directly lead to  the bioactivity of the compounds. As many glycosylated  products play a role as important pharmaceutical agents, 60  shows significant activity against Staphylococcus aureus  (Table 2). Also, it has cytotoxicity against HCT-116 with  an  IC50 value of 0.51 µM.

Cycloaspeptide  A  (61,  Fig.  13)  was  first  isolated  from  Aspergillus sp. NE-45 (Kobayashi et al. 1987) and was then  identified in S. arenicola (Bose et al. 2014b). This com- pound is a cyclic peptide containing anthranilic acid (ABA),  which is an ortho-substituted benzene ring with a carbox- ylic acid and an amine. Notably, cycloaspeptide A presented low cytotoxicity  towards human lung fibroblasts with an  IC50 of ≥ 1000 µM. Cyclomarins A, C, D and Cyclomarazines A and B

Cyclomarins A and C (62 and 63, Fig. 14) were identified  in S. arenicola CNS-205 isolated from Palau (Williams  et al. 2007b). These cyclic heptapeptides were first reported  from  the  marine-derived Streptomyces  strain  CNB-982  (Renner  et  al.  1999).  Cyclomarins  contain  seven  amino  acids; however, four of them are unusual. In addition to an  alanine, valine, and methyl-leucine, the other four unique  amino acids include 2-amino-3,5-dimethylhex-4-enoic acid,  N-(1,1-dimethyl-2,3-epoxypropyl)-β-hydroxytryptophan,  N-prenyltryptophan, and β-methoxyphenylalanine. Particu- larly, 2-amino-3,5-dimethylhex-4-enoic acid and N-(1,1- dimethyl-2,3-epoxypropyl)-β-hydroxytryptophan had not  been previously described. Although compound 62 is cyto- toxic against cancer cells in vitro with an  IC50 value 2.6 µM,  it was also found to possess anti-inflammatory activity in the  phorbol ester (PMA)-induced mouse model. Upon further  investigation of the chemical components of culture broth,  the strain CNS-205 was also found to produce another cyclic  heptapeptide, cyclomarin D (64) (Schultz et al. 2008). This  compound differs from 63 by the absence of the N-methyl  group. Moreover, compound 64 exhibited HCT-116 cytotox- icity, with an  IC50 of 1.97 µM.

Cyclomarazines A and B (65 and 66, Fig.  14), also  known as salinisporazines A and B, were also isolated  from the strain CNS-205 (Schultz et al. 2008). Two dike- topiperazine dipeptides could share a common biogenesis  pathway with cyclomarins. Functional characterization of  the prenyltransferase CymD in the cyclomarin pathway  provided a mechanism to synthesize N-alkylated trypto- phan derivatives in the cyclomarin series. A key structural  Fig. 14   Chemical structures of  cyclomarins (62–64) and cyclo- marazines (65 and 66) difference between cyclomarins (62–64) and cyclomara- zines (65 and 66) is the tryptophan moiety. Cyclomara- zines contain a tryptophan residue, but cyclomarins pos- sess a hydroxy group at the β-position of the tryptophan  unit. Compounds 65 and 66 displayed antibacterial activi- ties with MIC values of 45.20 and 33.84 µM against S.  aureus and E. faecium, respectively. Desferrioxamine B (67, Fig. 15) was produced by strain  CNS-205, CNT-088 and CNH-643 along with S. tropica  strain CNB-440 (Roberts et al. 2012). Desferrioxamine B  (67), also known as deferoxamine is a siderophore, a mol- ecule secreted by bacteria to capture irons with high affinity.   (Kb =  1031). It has long chain consisting of one acetic acid,  two succinic acid and three 1-amino-5-hydroxylaminopen- tane (Keberle 1964). Compound 67 was clinically approved  for medical use in the United States in 1968 due to its non- toxicity and ability to treat acute iron poisoning and chronic  aluminum overload. It can remarkably reduce serum ferri- tin level and hepatic iron (Mobarra et al. 2016). Compound  67 also shows significant antioxidant activity even at low

Neolymphostins A and B (70 and 71, Fig.  18), a closely- related derivative of lymphostin, were produced by treatment  of crude extract from the strain CNY-486 with a cysteine- based probe in trimethylamine and N,N-dimethylformamide  (Castro-Falcón et al. 2018). It led to formation of two pairs  of diastereomeric adducts, showing combinations of the  probe and neolympostin. Compound 70 showed strong affin- ity for PI3K  [Kd = 0.88 (α), 5.7 (β), 3.5 (γ), and 4.9 (δ)  nM] and mTOR  (Kd = 10 nM) and good ability to inhibit  class I PI3K, AKT phosphorylation with an estimated  IC50  of ~ 3 nM. Retimycin A (72, Fig. 19) is a quinomycin-like depsipeptide  that was identified in S. arenicola strain CNT-005 (Duncan  et al. 2015). It possesses cytotoxicity against HCT-116 cells  with an inhibitory concentration of < 0.06 µM. This com- pound has a symmetric structure, with a sulfur atom as its  axis of rotation. In addition to the sulfoxide and the meth- ylene present in its structure, both sides have two aromatic  rings and a cyclopropane ring. Rifamycins are a group of polyketide antibiotics consisting  of an aliphatic ansa chain connected to an aromatic chromo- phore. Rifamycins are RNA polymerase-targeting antibacte- rial drugs against Gram-positive bacteria, as well as Gram- negative bacteria to a lesser extent. They are widely used as  treatments for infections including tuberculosis. Rifamycin B (73, Fig. 20) was isolated from S. arenicola  strain M413 and is a precursor for other rifamycin analogs  Fig. 19   Chemical structure of retimycin A (72) Fig. 20   Formation of rifamycin S (75) from rifamycin B (73)

(Bose et al. 2015). Seven natural rifamycins were isolated  from Nocardia mediterranei, and compound 73 was chosen  for the development of clinical applications due to its stabil- ity, ease of purification, and solubility at physiological pH  conditions (Banerjee et al. 1992). However, this compound  did not exhibit antibacterial activity (Wehrli and Staehelin  1971). Rifamycin O (74, Fig. 20) was reported in a strain col- lected  along  the  Great  Barrier  Reef  (Queensland,  Aus- tralia) (Bose et al. 2014a). Compound 74 is an analog of  73 obtained via oxidation (Bacchi et al. 1998). It strongly  inhibited  Mycobacterium  abscessus,  a  nontuberculous  mycobacteria, with an  MIC50 value of 3.9 µM. Further- more, this compound exhibited an  MIC90 of 4.0–6.2 μM  against the pathogen strain, which is much stronger than  that of rifampicin (also known as rifampin). Treatment of  compound 74 in M. abscessus-injected zebrafish enhanced  lifespan up to 13 days, which was similar to the outcome of  rifabutin treatment (Hanh et al. 2020). Rifamycin S (75, Fig. 20) was also reported in the strain  S. arenicola strain M413 along with compound 73 and could  be obtained from the hydrolysis of 74 (Bose et al. 2015).  This compound is clinically important, as it is a key inter- mediate for the production of diverse synthetic drugs derived  from rifamycins. The MIC value for compound 75 in Table 4  is indicative of antibacterial activity against Gram-positive  bacteria and mycobacteria (Sensi et al. 1960).

A mixture of rifamycin SV (76), 27-O-demethyl-25-O- desacetylrifamycin SV (77), and 27-O-demethylrifamycin  SV (78) was reported to be produced by S. arenicola strain  CNS-205 (Fig. 21) (Wilson et al. 2010). Compound 76 is an  analog of 73 without the glycolic group in its molecule and  possesses a much higher bioactivity. Compound 76 is the  first rifamycin used in clinical settings along with semisyn- thetic rifamycin derivatives such as rifampicin, rifabutin, and  rifapentine. Compound 76 exhibited strong activity against  Clostridium difficile strains with an  MIC50 value of 0.07 µM  (Farrell et al. 2011). Salinaphthoquinones A–E (83–87, Fig. 23) were isolated  from S. arenicola strain BRA-213 collected from sediments  of the St. Peter and St. Paul Archipelago in Brazil (da Silva  et al. 2019b). Salinaphthoquinones belong to the aminon- aphthoquinone class. Four of them (83, 84, 86, and 87) are  2-aminonaphthoquinones and the remaining compound (85)  is a 3-aminonaphthoquinone. The amino group in the aminonaphthoquinone moiety is  mostly found at the C-2 position of the naphthoquinone  moiety, and naturally-occurring 3-aminonaphthoquinones  such as compound 85 are relatively rare. Saliniketals A and B (88 and 89, Fig. 24) have been isolated  from the S. arenicola strains CNR-005 and CNR-059 (Wil- liams et al. 2007a). Salinisporamycin (104, Fig. 27) was isolated from S. aren- icola strain YM23-082, which was obtained from marine  sediment  collected  in  Yap  State  (Federated  States  of  Micronesia) (Matsuda et al. 2009). Compound 104 inhib- ited human lung adenocarcinoma cell line A549 prolifera- tion, with an  IC50 value of 5.03 µM. This compound has antimicrobial  activity against fungi and yeast and has an  LD50 of 6.6 mg/ kg in mice when injected intraperitoneally. The  two  compounds,  N-(3-oxodecanoyl)-L-homoserine  lactone (110) and N-(3-oxododecanoyl)-L-homoserine lac- tone (111) were reported in S. arenicola (Fig.  31) (Bose  et al. 2017). These two compounds are members of acyl  homoserine lactones (AHLs) which are a class of signaling  molecules involved in bacterial quorum sensing, a method  of communication between bacteria. By producing N-AHLs  within the bacterial cell and releasing into the environment,  bacteria respond to environmental influences such as the  presence of other bacteria and then consequently respond by  changing behavior on a population density. The production  of AHL compounds from S. arenicola is significant report,  due to lack of production from Gram-positive marine bacte- ria compared to terrestrial Gram-negative bacteria. 4‑Hydroxy‑pyran‑2‑one  and 3‑hydroxy‑N‑methyl‑2‑oxindole derivatives Three  3-hydroxy-N -methyl-2-oxindoles  (112–114),  4-hydroxy-pyran-2-one (115), and 6-methoxy-N-methyli- satin (116) have been identified in S. arenicola strain BRA- 213 isolated from sediments of the St. Peter and St. Paul  Archipelago, Brazil (Fig. 32) (da Silva et al. 2019a). Among  them, 112, 113, and 115 were new natural products and the  remaining two were known compounds. Only 114 and 116  were active against Enterococcus faecalis with a MIC value  of 80.41 and 81.25 µM, respectively. Secondary metabolites isolated from Salinispora  pacifica and their biological activities

Cyanosporasides A–E (117–121, Fig. 33) were isolated from  S. pacifica strains CNS-103 and CNS-143 obtained from  sediments collected at a 500 m depth in Palau (Oh et al.  2006; Lane et al. 2013). Compounds 117 and 118 contain the  aglycone chromophore, a unique 3,3a-dihydrocyclopenta[a] indene ring system. The aglycone chromophore originates  from a polyketide biosynthetic pathway required for the syn- thesis of the enediyne core. This structure has been reported  only in sporolides, another type of natural products. The  sporolides are multicyclic chloroaromatic metabolites that  have been reported in different species of the genus Salinis- pora. The chemical analysis of S. pacifica strain CNS-143  revealed that several unreported cyanosporaside derivatives  are closely related to the previously described compound  118 (Lane et al. 2013). Compound 119 is an analog of 118  with an acetyl group at the C-4′. Both 120 and 121 have the  same aglycone found in 118 without the deoxysugar moi- ety. Moreover, compound 120 possesses an acetyl group  at position C-3, whereas 121 lacks an acetyl group at this  position. Only compound 117 was found to exhibit a weak  cytotoxic effect against human colon carcinoma HCT-116  cells  (IC50 = 68.18 µM). Enterocin (123, Fig. 35) is a bacteriostatic polyketide with a  highly uncommon structure including a caged tricyclic and  nonaromatic core with a Favorskii-like oxidative rearrange- ment of a reactive poly(β-carbonyl) substrate catalyzed by  the unusual flavoenzyme, EncM (Bonet et al. 2015). When  comparing the NMR spectra of S. pacifica CNT-150-derived  enterocin and standard enterocin, it was confirmed that the  compounds were identical. Therefore, S. pacifica CNT-150  is the first bacterium outside the Streptomyces genus shown  to produce compound 123. This compound possesses bac- teriostatic properties against Gram-positive and Gram-neg- ative bacteria such as Escherichia coli, species of Proteus,  Sarcina, Staphylococcus, and Corynebacterium, but has no  activity against fungi and yeasts (Miyairi et al. 1976).

Lomaiviticins A and B (124 and 125, Fig.  36) were first  isolated  from  the  halophilic  actinomycete  strain  LL- 37I366. This strain was originally thought to be a new  species within Micromonospora lomaivitiensis, but sub- sequent phylogenetic analysis revealed that LL-37I366  was a strain of the S. pacifica (Janso et al. 2014). Later  on,  124  was  also  been  identified  in  the  fermentation  broths of a different S. pacifica strain, DPJ-0019 (Woo  et  al.  2012).  Compounds  124  and  125  are  complex   C2-symmetric microbial natural products that contain a  dimeric diazotetrahydrobenzo[b]fluorene (diazofluorene)  skeleton containing 2–4 dideoxyglycoside residues, as well  as oleandrose and N,N-dimethylpyrrolosamine moieties.  Compounds 124 and 125 are powerful antibiotics, as dem- onstrated by their MICs of 6 to 25 ng/spot. Moreover, 124  is an unusually potent anti-cancer agent, with  IC50 values  ranging from 72 nM to 7.3 pM against 24 cancer cell lines.  Furthermore, 124 induced double-strand decomposition of  DNA, thereby causing significant cytotoxicity to human  cancer cell panels at nanomolar to picomolar concentra- tions (Colis et al. 2014).

Lymphostin  (48,  Fig.  6)  is  a  pyrroloquinoline  alka- loid, a lymphocyte kinase inhibitor  (IC50 of 0.05 mM),  and a potent mTOR inhibitor. The immunosuppressant  compound  48  was  first  isolated  from Streptomyces  sp.  KY11783, but was thereafter also isolated from S. areni- cola  and S.  pacifica  (Miyanaga  et  al. 2011).  The  pro- duction conditions of 48 were first established with S.  arenicola strain MOSO-0003 in 12 different media that  ultimately  resulted  in  a ~ 64.52  µM  titer  in  the  M48-9  medium. Further studies also revealed that 5 out of 11  different marine-invertebrate derived S. pacifica strains  produced compound 48. Although most strains includ- ing DPJ-0024 produced 48 alone, strain DPJ-0019 was  found to produce a mixture of compound 48 analogs. As  a result, a simpler production medium containing only  Lomaiviticins C–E (47,  126, and 127, Fig.  36) were  isolated from strain DPJ-0019 (Woo et al. 2012). Com- pound 47 exhibited homology to 124, including oleandrose  and N,N-dimethylpyrrolosamine residues. Moreover, com- pounds 126 and 127 share similar NMR spectral features  with 47, suggesting that 126 and 127 are derivatives of 47  with O-methyl substitutes in one or two oleandros resi- dues. Compound 126 is a mixture of isomers with proxi- mal  or  distal  diazofluorene  methylation.  Cell  viability  studies have also determined that 47, 126, and 127 have  submicromolar antiproliferative properties. Salinipyrones A and B (129 and 130) and pacificanones A  and B (131 and 132) were isolated from S. pacifica strain  CNS-237,  which  was  obtained  from  sediment  in  Palau  Island (Fig. 38) (Oh et al. 2008). Compounds 129 and 131  are structurally related to polyketides and share the same  lipid tail. However, difference in the composition of their  head groups is γ-hydroxypyrone and cyclohexanone, respec- tively. It has been suggested the associated polyketide syn- thase (PKS) could skip the penultimate extension module  to yield the slightly smaller salinipyrone. Compounds 129  and 130 appear to be α-pyrone polyketides derived from the  combination of acetate and propionate precursors. Propi- onate polyketide α-pyrones are known to occur in marine  invertebrates such as sacoglossans and pulmonates, and  occasionally in actinomycetes. Compounds 131 and 132  bear a distinctive 1, 3, 5, 6-tetra-alkyl-substituted cyclohex- ane ring, which had not been previously reported in natural  products. Compounds 129–132 could be synthesized via a  type I polyketide biosynthetic pathway. These compounds  did not exhibit any significant cytotoxicity against HCT-116  Fig. 38   Chemical structures of  salinipyrones A and B (129 and  130) and pacificanones A and B  (131 and 132) human colon cancer cells nor displayed antibacterial/anti- fungal activities against MRSA, VRE, or amphotericin- resistant C. albicans. Compound 129 has been reported to  display moderate inhibition of interleukin-5 production by  50% at 34.25 µM in the mouse splenocyte model for allergic  inflammation.

Compound 133 possesses a γ-lactam-β-lactone  bicyclic carbon backbone, however, it does not have any  substitution at C-2. Compound 133 exhibited 20S protea- some (chymotrypsin-like) inhibitory activity, with an  IC50  of 4.6 ± 0.4 nM and was cytotoxic to the HTC-116 cell line   (IC50 of 988 ± 155 nM). Sixteen nitrogen-containing compounds (135–151, Fig. 41)  were present in S. pacifica strain CNS-863 liquid cultures  (Harig et al. 2017). Moreover, N,N′-diisobutylurea (149) and  N,N-diisobutyloxalamide (150) were identified through the  process of nitrogen-containing volatile synthesis. The nitro- gen atom from compounds 135–151 appears to have origi- nated from biogenic amines such as isobutyl-, isopentyl-,  and 2-methylbutylamine derived from amino acids such as  valine, leucine, and isoleucine. These amines condense with  small active aldehyde or acyl metabolites in bacteria to form  these compounds.

The study of the chemical properties of bioactive marine  natural products began with the characterization of pento- syl nucleosides from marine sponges. This established the  basis for the development of the first marine-derived drugs,  Ara-A and C, which exhibited significant anti-cancer activ- ity (Proksch et al. 2002). The successful isolation of bioac- tive compounds from primitive marine invertebrates led to  the isolation of up to 10,000 bioactive compounds from the  phylum Porifera, after which other marine invertebrates were  also investigated such as tunicates, cone snails, and bryozoan  (Hu et al. 2011; Leal et al. 2012). The most important disadvantage of marine natural prod- ucts was that most marine invertebrates could not be sustain- ably supplied to meet industrial demands. Total chemical  synthesis not only solved this problem but also provided  further medicinal chemistry information to facilitate lead  optimization. Specifically, semi-synthesis has been success- fully implemented to ensure a continuous supply of complex  chemical compounds. Fermentation might be another suc- cessful approach but may not be applicable for the produc- tion of marine animal-derived secondary metabolites. Recent advances in biotechnology have accelerated the  process of identifying the gene sequences associated with  the synthesis of specific compounds, as well as the chemical  structure of these compounds. Additionally, biotechnology  techniques provide an alternative route for bioactive natural  products supply via heterologous expression. These techni- cal advances emphasize the importance of the new bacte- rial strains for the pipeline of gene sequences for the novel  chemical scaffolds and bioactivities.

Based on the aforementioned observations, marine bacte- rial strains have become promising drug discovery targets  (Fenical 2020). 150 Metabolites have been identified in the  genus Salinispora alone, and the characterization of their  chemistry and biological activities has been ongoing since  2001, when lomaiviticins A and B were first reported. Inter- estingly, the three species that comprise the genus Salin- ispora produce various species-specific natural products,  except for lomaiviticin C and lymphostin. Nonetheless, there  have been reports of structurally-related compounds among  these species. Such is the case of the S. pacifica-derived  salinosporamide K, an analog that is structurally similar to  the salinosporamides isolated from S. tropica. Therefore,  further study of the therapeutic potential of these bacterial  strains will likely lead to the discovery of new drugs and  marine derived bioactive compounds.
